<p><b>Inform</b> is a <a href="/wiki/Programming_language" title="Programming language">programming language</a> and design system for <a href="/wiki/Interactive_fiction" title="Interactive fiction">interactive fiction</a> originally created in 1993 by <a href="/wiki/Graham_Nelson" title="Graham Nelson">Graham Nelson</a>. Inform can generate programs designed for the <a href="/wiki/Z-machine" title="Z-machine">Z-code</a> or <a href="/wiki/Glulx" title="Glulx">Glulx</a> virtual machines. Versions 1 through 5 were released between 1993 and 1996. Around 1996, Nelson rewrote Inform from <a href="/wiki/First_principle" title="First principle">first principles</a> to create version 6 (or <b>Inform 6</b>).<sup id="cite_ref-spag44_2-0" class="reference"><a href="#cite_note-spag44-2">[2]</a></sup> Over the following decade, version 6 became reasonably stable and a popular language for writing interactive fiction. In 2006, Nelson released <b>Inform 7</b> (briefly known as <b>Natural Inform</b>), a completely new language <a href="/wiki/Natural_language_programming" title="Natural language programming">based on principles of natural language</a> and a new set of tools based around a book-publishing metaphor.</p>
<p></p>
